00:56:39.960 --> 00:56:42.290
And I can't tell you-- people
come to me and say, you know,

00:56:42.290 --> 00:56:43.200
I'm talking.

00:56:43.200 --> 00:56:46.900
I just did my TED Talk, I've
been blogging like crazy.

00:56:46.900 --> 00:56:48.050
I've got to have the book.

00:56:48.050 --> 00:56:49.700
Everybody wants the book.

00:56:49.700 --> 00:56:52.270
And if you think about, the book
does a lot of things for

00:56:52.270 --> 00:56:53.970
you that nothing else does.

00:56:53.970 --> 00:56:57.080
So, I mean, people still think
of it as sort of the ultimate

00:56:57.080 --> 00:56:58.420
emblem of learning.

00:56:58.420 --> 00:56:59.530
I can write a book.

00:56:59.530 --> 00:57:03.140
We've been told forever that
book is the ultimate

00:57:03.140 --> 00:57:04.880
expression.

00:57:04.880 --> 00:57:10.150
It's this very handy device you
can just hand to people.

00:57:10.150 --> 00:57:12.590
It's an entry to the ideaplex
because that's how

00:57:12.590 --> 00:57:12.950
you get into it.

00:57:12.950 --> 00:57:16.350
You say, his new book,
as opposed to he just

00:57:16.350 --> 00:57:18.460
posted a cat video.

00:57:18.460 --> 00:57:20.460
That's not getting you
on Charlie Rose.

00:57:20.460 --> 00:57:21.900
You got to have--

00:57:21.900 --> 00:57:23.820
the book does a lot
of things for you.

00:57:23.820 --> 00:57:28.165
But, you know, your criticism
is very well taken.

00:57:28.165 --> 00:57:29.300
Many people feel the same way.

00:57:29.300 --> 00:57:30.890
Do I need to read this
entire book?

00:57:30.890 --> 00:57:32.890
And often, you don't.

00:57:32.890 --> 00:57:35.890
AUDIENCE: Have you written
an article form of this?

00:57:35.890 --> 00:57:37.874
JOHN BUTMAN: We did--

00:57:37.874 --> 00:57:40.950
we have not written an article
in "HBR," but we've done

00:57:40.950 --> 00:57:44.518
articles in various different
places, yeah.

00:57:44.518 --> 00:57:46.446
Other questions?

00:57:46.446 --> 00:57:46.928
Yes.

00:57:46.928 --> 00:57:50.302
AUDIENCE: So what is it the
metric that you are measuring

00:57:50.302 --> 00:57:51.266
yourself against?

00:57:51.266 --> 00:57:52.712
Is it tweets?

00:57:52.712 --> 00:57:54.650
Followers?

00:57:54.650 --> 00:57:56.620
JOHN BUTMAN: The number of--

00:57:56.620 --> 00:58:02.100
the number, fewer clients that
come to knock on our door.

00:58:02.100 --> 00:58:02.840
What is the metric?

00:58:02.840 --> 00:58:05.310
That's a really good one.

00:58:05.310 --> 00:58:07.575
The one on one metric really
means the most to me.

00:58:07.575 --> 00:58:10.210
And that's one I'm paying
most attention to.

00:58:10.210 --> 00:58:13.410
So that's kind of what
I'm focusing on now.

00:58:13.410 --> 00:58:16.120
And we're still in the
early days here.

00:58:16.120 --> 00:58:19.860
But if we could hear
people say--

00:58:19.860 --> 00:58:25.370
if we could get this model out
there and get some sense that

00:58:25.370 --> 00:58:28.320
people are kind of evaluating
ideas through this model, that

00:58:28.320 --> 00:58:29.570
would be great.

00:58:32.090 --> 00:58:32.390
Great.

00:58:32.390 --> 00:58:33.640
Thank you very much.

